-- Ibovespa Futures Rise as China Economic Data Boost Metal Prices
-- B y   N e y   H a y a s h i
-- 2013-10-08T12:23:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-08/ibovespa-futures-rise-as-china-economic-data-boost-metal-prices.html
Ibovespa  futures  gained, after the
equity index fell to a one-week low yesterday, as metals
advanced after data indicated growth in  China ’s services,
boosting the outlook for Brazilian raw-material exporters.  State-controlled oil producer Petroleo Brasileiro SA may be
active after saying it plans to close 38 units abroad to focus
on production and exploration projects in  Brazil . Mining company
Vale SA may move after saying the iron-ore market will probably
be oversupplied by 2015.  Ibovespa futures contracts expiring next week rose 0.2
percent to 52,005 at 9:21 a.m. in Sao Paulo. The real
strengthened 0.3 percent to 2.1989 per dollar. The Bloomberg
Base Metals 3-Month Price Commodity Index climbed 0.4 percent.  In China, Brazil’s biggest trading partner, a services
activity index was 52.4 last month compared with 52.8 in August,
according to data from HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit Economics. A
reading above 50 indicates expansion.  The Ibovespa entered a bull market Sept. 9 after rising 20
percent from this year’s low on July 3 through that day. The
gauge is still down 20 percent in dollar terms this year,
compared with a decline of 4.2 percent for the MSCI  Emerging
Markets  Index of 21 developing nations’ equities.  Trading volume of stocks in Sao Paulo yesterday was 4.83
billion reais, compared with a daily average of 7.62 billion
reais this year through Oct. 4, according to data compiled by
the exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ney Hayashi in Sao Paulo at 
